    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1044"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1044">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/1239</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The German Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BCJHV1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bernstorff</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Counselor for the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">German Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-21">
                        <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1914</hi>.</date> [<hi rend="italic">Received
                        December 22</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="flushleft">J. NO. A 3180]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_LR1"
                        >LANSING</persName>: I learn that the British <persName>S. S. <hi
                            rend="italic">Mallina</hi>
                    </persName> and <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Tremeadow</hi>
                    </persName>, which served as tenders to British cruisers, now demand to be
                    allowed to coal in Panama and to leave for Australia, alleging that they have
                    ceased to be tenders of British warships. I beg to draw your attention to the
                    fact that, as far as can be seen from here, their case, in the principal points,
                    is identical with the case of the German <persName>S. S. <hi rend="italic"
                            >Locksun</hi>
                    </persName>.<note n="1" xml:id="d1044fn1">See the section on treatment of
                        belligerent warships, their crews and tenders, in American ports— Internment
                        of the Geier and <hi rend="italic">Locksun—ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_583"
                            >583</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCJHV1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">J. Bernstorff</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
